-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_STMT_WHILE.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node AST
-- walker in hir_to_lir.c used locally-shadowed typedef guesses for
-- every IRON_NODE_* case it handled. The walker crashed on the IF
-- case (see hir_to_lir_elif_mono_walker.iron for the original bug
-- story); the same walker incompleteness class can resurface on any
-- other node kind if a future edit re-introduces a layout assumption.
-- Phase 66 added -Werror=switch-enum and _Static_assert on common
-- prefixes as structural protections. This canary is the runtime
-- regression net for IRON_NODE_WHILE: any walker case that fails to
-- recurse into the condition or body silently drops sub-expressions
-- from the lowered LIR, and this fixture turns red immediately.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_WhileStmt carries
--   { span, kind, condition, body }
-- Walker cases that mis-read this layout (e.g., confusing it with
-- Iron_IfStmt and indexing past `body` into garbage) produce the same
-- class of silent SIGSEGV the Phase 37-02 bug caused.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. CI integration: runs in both Debug and Release via Phase
-- 66-04's build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- the Phase 37-02 SIGSEGV
-- was deterministic on Linux Release for months. This canary closes
-- the per-kind coverage gap for while-loop lowering.

func sum_to(n: Int) -> Int {
  var sum = 0
  var i = 1
  while i <= n {
    sum = sum + i
    i = i + 1
  }
  return sum
}

func main() {
  println("sum: {sum_to(10)}")
}
